AGI - Shock on the Montmartre hill in Paris: the famous Moulin Rouge lost the blades, fallen in the night for reasons still unknown and without causing injury. The famous cabaret, however, will remain open to welcome its spectators. "Le Moulin is 135 years old, so he has experienced difficult times", said to the press Jean-Victor Clerico, general manager of the dean of the Parisian cabarets, "We will accept the challenge". The stars of the legendary mill, known all over the world and immortalized in particular by the homonymous film of Baz Luhrmann, fell around 1.45, about half an hour after the last spectators had left. The letters M, O and U also fell, placed on the facade. There is no risk of collapse, according to the Paris firefighters. It is the first time in its long history that the cabaret loses the blades, which had begun to turn on 6 October 1889, the evening of the inauguration of the premises.
&nbsp;
"It's amazing," said Exauce, the chef at Moulin Rouge, who found them on the ground when he arrived around 8:00 in the morning. At the moment we do not know the reasons for this collapse but the management claims to be able to exclude any "doloso act". "We have 24/7 surveillance, especially on roofs. We already know that this is not a painful act, it is of course a technical problem", said Jean-Victor Clerico "The Moulin Rouge will be open this evening to welcome our spectators", he assured.
&nbsp;
In the morning, barriers were put around the entrance, but the road was not blocked and a truck with tipping bin removed the blades. The clearance operations ended around 8.35. By "so much pain" spoke the ministra della Cultura, Rachida Dati, referring to a place "famous all over the world". Both the municipality and the ministry declared that they were ready to help the cabaret with repairs, and Mayor Hanne Hidalgo said to "discover" that the blades return to their place before the Olympics (July 26).
<div </div
The only serious incident occurred at the temple of the world cancan was a fire due to the works in 1915. The cabaret had to close for nine years. Made of wood and aluminium, the blades had been renovated about twenty years ago to "alread them", Clerico explained, and structure and motorization "are controlled every two months by a specialized company". The last maintenance was done on March 20. The place, located at the foot of the Montmartre hill and in the heart of the Pigalle district, is synonymous with crazy Parisian nights and with the Lido and cancan dancers, attracts thousands of visitors from all over the world every day. Immortized by the painter Toulouse-Lautrec, the Moulin Rouge welcomes 600,000 spectators a year, with two performances each evening, 365 days a year, and employs about 450 people.
