AGI - The consumption of alcohol and electronic cigarettes between 11-15-year-olds is "awesome" and requires urgent action by public authorities: It is read in a report from the European section of the Oms, which recommends public health measures to limit access to alcoholic beverages. "The widespread use of harmful substances among children in many countries of the European region - and not only - constitutes a serious threat to public health", said Hans Kluge, regional director of the World Health Organization mentioned in a note. In particular, in order to counter this trend, Kluge asks to increase taxes, to limit stores and advertising and to prohibit flavouring agents. After years of decline in the use of psychoactive substances, "some data suggest that the Covid-19 pandemic triggered a further increase in consumption", we read in the report, which collects data of 280.000 young people in Europe, Central Asia and Canada. Containment measures have changed boys' habits between 11 and 15 years. They were more present online and more exposed to digital advertising.
&nbsp;
According to the WHO, the adoption of risky behaviors during adolescence can affect behavior in adulthood, and the use of psychoactive substances in early age is linked to a higher risk of addiction. "Political leaders cannot afford to ignore these alarming results," adds the organization. Alcohol remains the most frequently consumed substance by adolescents: 57% of the 15-year-olds drank alcohol at least once and almost four out of ten have consumed alcohol in the last 30 days. "These results underline the extent to which alcohol is available and normalized and show the urgent need for better political measures to protect children and young people from (his) damage," the organization insists, which brings together 53 countries and extends to Central Asia. At the same time, Omnis is concerned about the use of electronic cigarettes, which has increased, especially among teenagers. "The transition to electronic cigarettes as a more popular choice than conventional cigarettes requires targeted interventions," writes the World Health Organization, which recommends "inserting harmful products in video games, entertainment programs and other content aimed at young people through multimedia platforms".

