AGI - Israel> continues preparations for the operation in Rafah>, in the extreme south of the Gaza Strip, waiting "very soon", according to the media. A senior Israeli security officer told the Reuters agency that the Israeli army is ready to launch an operation immediately to Rafah and is just waiting for the political path.
&nbsp;
The ground-offensive plan was presented to American officials and other agencies in the region, reports Israeli broadcaster Kan: it will proceed by stages, based on a regional division of the city in defined areas. At every stage and for each area, the army (Idf) will inform the population before moving forward so that civilians can leave shelters and homes for a long time.
&nbsp;
The armed forces announced that they had mobilized two brigades of reservists to return to southern Gaza and "continue the defence and attack mission in the Strip" under the command of the 99th Division. The second Reserve Brigade of 146th Division and the 679th Reserve Brigade of the 210th Division will be transferred from the north of Israel to the border with Lebanon.
&nbsp;
The Idf approved the last plan for Operation Rafah earlier this week, after three previous plans had been suggested. The American government has expressed firm opposition to an operation in the extreme south of Gaza without a credible plan to protect civilians. "We are preparing to establish a joint operation with the United States. We understand the concern, but we cannot complete the mission without entering Rafah, which could also help relieve pressure on the issue of hostages," said an official.
&nbsp;
Meanwhile, Axios reported citing three high Israeli officials, yesterday morning the head of Shin Bet, Ronen Bar, and Israeli chief of staff, Herzi Halevi, visited Egypt and met with the head of intelligence in Cairo and other key officials to discuss the imminent offensive. Egypt, with which Rafah borders, warned Israel from entering the city where more than a million displaced Palestinians reside, fled from other areas of the Strip because of the bombings. &nbsp;

